title: OmniStand Mod Backside addon Fillament Guide

description.text:
This is add-on to the OmniStand Mod Backside made by PeterS1 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1238389) for mostly 1KG (or bigger spools) as with bigger spools filament can fall off the rim and entangle around blocking printing. I have also included filament cleaner box, you could just put inside some sponge for cleaning filament before printing. Should be printed with following (I use Simplify3D for slicing):

  • 0.25 layer height
  • top/bottom layers 2
  • Infill at least 50% (70% would be perfect)
  • With 1mm support (with offset from part 0.70mm)

After printing, you can fixate this to the omnistand with some 3x16mm screws (I used 2) and drilled 2mm hole with drill before screwing in.

p.s. this is my first ever 3D print model, and first ever model done in 123D Design. Comments welcome :)

title: RunCam Swift ImpulseRC Alien back plate

description.text:
One of my favorite features of the ImpulseRC Alien is the indexed angle holes for mounting the FPV camera. Unfortunately the mount included with the Alien is meant for the HS1117 camera. I prefer to use the RunCam Swift. This part is a replacement back plate for the Swift to which you mount the tabs included with the Alien camera mount which will allow you to use the index holes on the K plates.
The back plate has some small details to it so you need to have a well calibrated printer. Also, I recommend using PETG or other dimensionally stable material.

Update Sept 26, 2016: I didn't like how the original part lined up with the bottom of the back plate, not with the camera housing. So I added a lip to the bottom and rounded off the bottom corner.

The STL file as uploaded is the basic generic form of the output of the OpenSCAD file; if you want tiles with other hex layouts, to change the texture of the face of the tile from a blank hexagon, or generate half-height (textureless) tiles, use the Customizer.

I have added several sample heightfield files for use as the tile face texture source; preview the file and save it to your desktop, then pick that file in the Customizer as the face texture.

An additional parameter has been added that controls whether or not a heightfield file will be used to texture the raised center of the hex faces; if this parameter is set to 'no', a blank raised hex face will be used, giving tiles like the ones in the uncustomized hex tile download.

Added a parameter to generate a minimal support structure for the underside of the tile faces to address bridging issues, which can be easily clipped out.

Printer:

Flux Delta

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

Medium

Infill:

10%

Notes:

The first layer on the underside in the center is a tough test for bridging for ground tiles, but the version of Slic3r that the frontend software uses doesn't think supports are needed; I get the same print whether I have supports on or off.

The tiles should print out at the proper scale; a single-hex tile will be 50.77mm on the long axis.

Bridging cleanup

If you haven't printed with supports, the first layer of filament laid over the central hollow will almost certainly have a tangle at the widest point where your printer couldn't make the filament reach all the way across; this will need to be clipped out. Water tiles (half-height) are printed with the top face down, and won't have this issue.

The OpenSCAD file has been updated to increase the variety of tiles that may be generated:

single -- single-hex tile
pair -- two-hex tile
row3, row4, row5 -- three-, four-, or five-hex straight tile
tri3 -- three-hex triangle tile
diam4 -- four-hex diamond-shape tile
block6 -- two-by-three hex tile
rnd7 -- tile with six hexes around a central hex

Each of these can be created as a 'ground' hex -- a full-height tile that can have a custom texture file applied to the center of each hex face -- or a 'water' hex -- a half-height tile with no face texture. Water tiles are printed face down to eliminate any bridging issues.

The texture file must be a 150x150 or larger image; larger images will be scaled. White in the image is high; black is low.

Note: A 'ground' tile without a face texture file selected prints without a center face; I have not yet figured out how to determine if no file is selected and apply a default face block. However, the uncustomized thing has 'blank' tiles for each of the ground tile types, so you can simply use those.

description.text:
I've been working on adding magnetic bases to my 6-player Settlers of Catan set, using the excellent dividers and organizers uploaded by dassmilytier over here - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1749597 . However, I don't care for the seafarers expansion. My favorite thing about Catan is the simplicity, so we usually stick to the base-game, although we sometimes have 5 or 6 players.

Using dassmilytier's organizers with the particular box I had available, I found that the only way to fit the entire 6-player game in the box I'm using was to modify a couple of his models. The two models I've uploaded attach in place of the end-plate, and hold either a single 21mm tile, or two 12mm tiles. (the 12mm box end is just slightly thicker than it needs to be so that they have the same exterior dimensions as the 21mm box end)

This allowed me to lay out the boxes in 4 pairs, each with one of these on the end:

Trophy/token holders & 12mm Box End
36mm, 1x26mm & 21mm Box End
2x21mm & 21mm Box End
2x26mm & 21mm Box End

The 12mm box end holds the two desert tiles, one of the 21's holds a regular tile, and the other two each hold two of the 6-player expansion borders. (they're a half tile, so the expansion borders fit nicely two to a slot).

description.text:
Update: it turned out this didn't actually work. What finally fixed the problem (only just recently!) was running the steppers with 24V, which also enabled them to run at their specified current (and more quietly/better sounding). I probably also significantly reduced voltage fluctuations in the process.  
My bot has had a real problem with the filament drive wheel slipping for a long time now, which would occasionally result in stripping, especially on long prints, and thus lots of frustration and wasted plastic. Jag's filament drive proved to have less slipping, but there was still too much. Fortunately his design has the advantage of being uncovered, so that some airflow can reach the filament and the drive components and escape from the other side. Thus it was a simple matter to print a mount for a small fan that could push air across the drive. This has almost completely eliminated slippage (huzzah!).

Print. The mount attaches to the acrylic at the stock t-slot with a M3x20 bolt. M3 bolts are used to attach a 40mm fan to the mount. The fan can be wired to the extruder stepper fan in parallel. The scad file also has the beginnings of a mount for a common 90mm computer case fan.

Firstly... KUDOS to the amazing work of BillyMcCoy. Fantastic model and a lot of fun to build.
Ive built a few of these and never really liked the idea of gluing the joints. So i redesigned the joints to include larger holes and other such changes to allow M3x12mm screws and nuts.

Also added a lock part that holds the head onto the cross shaft so it can easily be turned without the head falling off. THIS PART MUST BE INSTALLED PRIOR TO ASSEMBLING THE CROSS SHAFT TO THE CROSS PLATE

Changed the back of the head to include a flange for easier positioning.

Please let me know if you make this and encounter any problems at all!!

Thanks everyone!

description.text:
I have a wire "perimeter fence" around the yard, the bulk pack stakes that came with it are OK most of the time, but in places they just pull out of loose sandy soil. Bigger stakes come $15 for a pack of 50, and they're better, but still inadequate in some places.

Today, I needed 3 more "big" stakes, so I decided to print them instead of buying another pack. The .gx file has the stake scaled up to 150mm long, which makes good wall thickness. If you want to vary the stake size much from 6" you might want to go into the .blend file and change the thickness of the body to meet your needs/desires.

Printer:

Flashforge Dreamer

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.30

Infill:

N/A

Notes:

I've been printing these on high-speed, low quality defaults (ABS @ 235C, table at 105C), and I'm pleased with the results.

I've printed about 20 of these now, including multiple prints up to 6 at a time. It's probably the easiest printing design I've ever tried to print, maybe in large part because I'm printing them low quality, high thickness high temperature ABS.

One prints in about 25 minutes, after preheating, I printed 6 at once and they took right around 150 minutes - no time savings, but you can get 6 at a time without fooling with the machine.

Hammer Carefully

The head could be a bit thicker if you really need to hammer the part hard into the ground, I haven't had any breakage, but I did see the ABS discolor from black to white after a couple of hard hammer blows. Still, in my soil, I was able to hammer these all the way down under the ground surface without any breakage.

Extruded poly-lines

Blender takes a bit of getting used to, but if you rotate properly, you can make parts like this without mesh, just a collection of extruded closed polyline shapes.

Problem: There has been a report of the heat bed springs possibly being able to scratch through the electrically insulated layer of the heat bed. This can cause the spring to electrically conduct the voltage and amperage at the spring contact point of the heat bed circuit to the metal plate located below the heatbed. In some cases the movement of the heat bed during printing can cause another contact to short this voltage to ground, causing a safety hazard. For further information please refer to the following YouTube video:

Fix: There is a simple fix. Please print off four of the following insulated washers and install between the heatbed and securing nuts located under the heatbed . description.text:
Honda has been having issues with sun visors for several years and unfortunately visor of 2016 Civic has design flaws as well.The mounting arm of the visor is so loose that, when the visor is turned along the door, during a sharp left turn, it may hit driver's head (happened to me few times). IMHO, this may even cause an accident if the driver does not expect such hit. In Honda Service center I was told that there is no way to fix it - nothing to tighten, so I decided to come up with my own 3d printed solution. It may work for other Honda models as well.

I removed driver's hand grip (which is useless in my opinion) and replaced it with visor clip. Since the grip has 2 mounting points, I designed cover for one of them and attached the clip to another. Images show how it all came together. Unfortunately this solution does not allow to adjust visor position along the door, but the clip is far back enough to well protect from the side sunlight. I'd be happy to see remixes of this design addressing this limitation.

Parts

You will need one 4mm self-locking nut and three M4x20mm screws - two should have hex socket cups and one should have hex head.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

VERTEX K8400

Rafts:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

holder_outer was printed with Touching Bed support. All other things were printed without brim or support.

holder_outer and cover things contain support structures that need to be removed after printing. Assemble all the pieces and tighten all screws at least once before mounting them to the car.

After removing hand grip (how-to instructions can be found on the web) push the cover thing into the right hole of the grip until it clicks. Place hex-head screw into inner_piece and slide it into the left hole by holding the other end of the screw. Pull the screw back with your hand until inner_piece fills the opening from inside. Use a knife or other sharp and flat tool to apply pressure to the far end of the screw from left to right direction. This will help holding the screw in position and stop it from being pushed back while you mount holder_inner piece. The screw should pass through holder_inner and come out for about 4-5mm. Fix these 2 things in this position with self-locking nut. This is a bit tricky operation and may take few tries until you succeed.
Instead of a knife you can use few drops of silicon to glue the screw to inner_piece and to glue inner_piece to the surroundings of the opening from inside. Let silicon dry before you proceed.
Place holder_outer thing on top of holder_inner and fix it in this position with 2 hex socket cup screws from the right side.

Specific hole configuration allows multiple orientations when used zip-tied to a server rack.

In addition, the hole configuration and side screwdriver opening also allow for multiple surface mounting options direct to wood, wallboard, etc using standard wood screws. Supports unnecessary with addition of new center support inside of screwdriver opening, now separated into 2 smaller openings as opposed to original single full length opening.

Different infill % will provide for different elasticity of fixed arms.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A housing for the Raspberry Pi Model B board with space to mount the camera board including a camera hole.
The camera is screwed into the top part of the housing with 4 M2 screws. These can be screwed directly into the holes, no tapping required. The two halfes of the housing are screwed together with 2 M3 screws, these are also screwed directly into the holes. I made this housing to be screwed to our acrylic housing on the replicator, that is why the holes go all the way through the hosuing. I used the RPi CAD file from RS and a CAD file of the camera board I found on the web.
I've included the step file of the housing so you can modify it to your needs. UPDATE 14.11.13: I've added a version of the bottom half with air cracks in it, in case you are worried the RPi will get to hot.
I printed this on a Replicator 1 Dual in Makerware with the standard PLA profile and no support

title: NinjaFlex Bouncy Balls with Internal Lattice

description.text:
When I got NinjaFlex working on my 3D printer, my first goal was was to make a bouncy ball. I was disappointed when due to the 2D infill provided by my slicer, the ball was not consistent in how high or where it bounced. By using Maker Muse's method for creating even, 3D infill, I was able to engineer a better bouncy ball.

Video: https://youtu.be/JWwllOorjUw

Here is a list of the different versions you can download and how they are different:
Version 0: This was the first attempt at making a NinjaFlex bouncy ball. It is just a plain sphere and does not bounce well or consistently. It bounced anywhere from 1' 10" to 2' 8"

Version 1: This was the first attempt at using a 3D cubic lattice to improve bounciness. It was very dense and too hard. It had a wall thickness of 2mm, a tube thickness of 3mm, and a density of 7.5mm.

Version 2: This was the second try using the cubic lattice. It produced great results. It was not too dense, bounced very well, and bounced consistently. It had 4mm wall thickness, 4mm tube thickness, and 10mm density. On average, it bounces 3' 9".

Version 3: The third attempt yielded worse results than the previous one. It bounced less, (averaging 3' 4") and less consistently. It had a 3mm wall thickness, a 3mm tube thickness, and a 18mm density.

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2-.4

Infill:

4 shells

Notes:

If you want to make your own, I suggest you print Version 2.

I heavily recommend printing with a raft and minor supports in order to hold up the print since it has no flat surface.

Expansion and Applications

Upon further investigation, I found that there is a fundamental limit to how "consistently bouncy" a 3D printed structure can be. This is a result of 3D printed flexible materials being more elastic in parallel with the layer lines. This results in the ball bouncing best when it's layers are parallel with the surface it is bouncing off of. Paradoxically, 3D printing is the only manufacturing technology that can make this geometry, making this limit unavoidable.

This knowledge, along with the designs and information of the project itself could have many applications in controlled compliancy and metamaterials. If the density of the lattice were to be different throughout a 3D object, the finished print would have varying compliancy, i.e., different levels of softness. This is a vital function to mechanical metamaterials. Most compliant metamaterials are based on 2-dimensional structures. This is great for mimicking simple and linear mechanisms, but is not as suitable for more complex systems. A 3D metamaterial structure could potentially solve this bottleneck. Although this is mostly hypothetical right now, I am researching the concept.

After fighting with Bowden setups on my E-bot I took the plunge and bought a Titan by E3D. Having to mount this I developed a new standard mounting plate for my E-bot. This plate has a pattern of holes with space for 4-40 nuts to be inserted. This provides great strength and maximum flexibility in parts and upgrade.

Also included with these plates are the mount for the Titan and E3D V-6 hotend. A mount and duct for a 40mm fan. A mount for a capacitive sensor for auto bed leveling and a mount for zip tying your cables to the carriage. Printed at 0.2mm layer thickness with 2 perimeters and 30% infill out of ABS.

Step and STL files provided.
ATTRIBUTION:
E3D Titan Extruder model found in the Step file was produced Ben Neubauer as found on GrabCAD

KNOWN ISSUES:

  • Belt clamp is 2mm prouder than it should be. This causes the belt to approach the carriage from a slight angle. The closest the carriage can come to the belt bearings is 12mm. This distance along with the 2mm proudness and pythagoras tells us that this induces an error at the extreme min and max of the printer of 0.17 mm (0.0065 in). Due to the small nature of this error and how quickly small angles dominate I chose to rather have a thicker plate then a perfectly parallel belt.

  • Belt clamps seem weaker than I would like. Probably should print with 100% infill.

EDITS

  • Added a left fan duct that has room for the hotend wires to run beside it.
  • Replaced the Titan Mount with a new more robust version. On the old version, when the nozzle was too close to the bed, the drive gear would push on the filament and bend the titan mounting plate backwards. This fatigued the part and would have eventually cause the mount to break.
  • Added BLTouch mount as a remix
  • Added RJ-45 jack mount as a remix

title: Car or wall mount gripping smartphone holder system

description.text:
This is a "gripping" smartphone holder than depending on the attachment you use, can mount in a car or to a wall. The gripping action is achieved with a rubber band.

Some features / design goals

  1. One handed insertion of phone. The back plates have a locking mechanism so they won't slide off accidentally.
    Just slide the top edge of the phone in and up and then when high enough, seat the bottom of the phone in the holder.
  2. One holder, multiple mounting options.
    Mount to wall, car vent or CD slot. Other attachments can be created and swapped out.
  3. NO SUPPORT NEEDED for ANY part.
    I print the CD Slot attachment at an angle with a raft and it prints without supports.

To swap mounting attachments, you can pinch the arches on the back plates to slide them off of the holder. When you slide in a back plate, it will slide in with a satisfying click.

I've made a straight vent clip (no swivel joint) and also a swivel vent clip. The straight attach vent clips come in vertical or horizontal versions. The swivel version works with both vent orientations.

I created the wall mount for a friend who needed to attach it to a camper (RV). 3M command strips work well.

Make sure the threaded nut screws on straight. Do not cross thread. Tightening the nut stiffens the holders position. Adjust the nut accordingly.

The threaded nut is stiff at first. Work it on and off a few times and it will work just fine.

I remixed the CD mount. I was going to design one but found one that looked good and had good comments. I made some minor changes to work with my mounting system.

The difference between the CD mount files is that one prints without supports (just a raft and printing at the proper angle, see blue build plate picture). The other requires support. Your option.

description.text:
After using a gregfrost extruder on my Prusa for a while, I decided I wanted to make a few tweaks to the basic design:

  • replace the hobbed bolt (I found it too strip-prone) with a large-diameter filament driver that requires no machining

  • a spring-loaded over-center latch on the idler arm, allowing opening the idler without unscrewing anything

  • an idler arm that opens flat to provide even better access to inspect & clean the filament drive
    • After assembling it and running a few test parts, I put it to work building parts for sublime's printed lathe, around 45 hrs of runtime with 14 hrs for the longest single build, and didn't experience a single hiccup. I have since run it at up to 100mm/s, which it handles fine. The extruder body has mounting provision for the Makergear hotend. Zip file contains the Solidworks 2011 source files.

If you have a gregfrost extruder, you can re-use all the parts of it except the body, the idler arm, and the hardware connecting the two. Print the extruder body in ABS. No support should be required; there are built-in removable supports where needed. The rest of the parts can be ABS or PLA as you prefer. Driver drum The filament driver drum can be made from a McMaster-Carr aluminum spacer P/N 92510A797 (current price $2.32). The drawing shows the dimensions if you want to machine your own. Use the drill jig to tap drill for 2 6-32 holes in the drum (if the drum is loose in the jig, tap 2 of the jig holes for 6-32 clamp screws). Tap the holes & install 2 6-32 x 3/16 setscrews. Clamp an 8-32 tap into the crank handle for the hobbing jig with a 6-32 screw on each side. Tap the small holes under each bearing cutout in the hobbing jig 6-32 and insert a screw in each one. Assemble the drum into the hobbing jig with 2 608 bearings and an M8 bolt & nut, tightening the drum screws to align the drum centerline with the hobbing jig centerline. Insert the tap/crank into the jig, snug the bearing screws just enough to put the drum in contact with the tap, and spin the crank a few times. Remove the nut and pull the bolt & drum out to check that the hobbing is indeed centered, adjust if necessary, and re-assemble. Start cranking, tightening the bearing screws periodically until the hobbed groove is about 1/2 filament diameter deep. Latch link The wire link for the latch is made from a steel wire pushrod made for R/C airplanes, so you'll probably have to visit a hobby shop to get one. If you can't find one locally, see http://www3.towerhobbies.com/cgi-bin/wti0001p?&I=LXD871&P=7 . Bend to the drawing. Assembly Cut a piece of the leftover pushrod wire a bit shorter than the width of the latch lever, and use it to attach the pivot block to the lever. Cut two short pieces of filament to act as pins for the lever, gluing them to the tabs on the body. Insert the threaded end of the wire link through the pivot block and put on the idler spring and 4-40 locknut. Install the main bearings, big gear, bolt, driver drum, and locknut. Adjust the driver drum position so the hobbing is in line with the filament path. Install the idler bearing and its pin into the arm. Use a 6-32 screw to hinge the idler arm to the body. I printed and liked the E3D adapter mount designed by Brian Benchoff (Monoprice MP Select Mini E3D Hotend Adapter), but the standard E3D heatsink and fan do not provide any cooling to the filament. I wanted to improve bridging capability on my printer without dividing airflow between the heatsink and filament, so I created a remixed version of his adapter that adds a mount for a dedicated 40mm filament cooling fan.

It assembles using the M3 hardware from his adapter and one M6 bolt and nut. I wired the filament fan into the regular heatsink fan circuit and it works well.

description.text:
The Providence-class carrier/destroyer, additionally designated as the Dreadnaught-class command ship and also known as the Trade Federation cruiser, the Separatist Star Destroyer, or the Separatist dreadnought, was a series of capital ship models fielded by the Confederate Navy during the Clone Wars. Providence-class ships were massive, cylindrical 1,088-meter-long warships with a pointed nose that tapered towards the superstructure. Some Providence-class vessels were longer, measuring 2,177.35 meters. These ships were said to be some of the biggest in the Separatist fleet and were capable of holding a planetary blockade almost by themselves.[8] This enlarged model was billed as the "Separatist Dreadnought".[1] Rising from the stern portion of the vessel, was an elongated main communications and sensor pod.[7] The ships, like all Mon Calamari and Quarren designs, were designed to be capable of landing on water in case of emergencies.

description.text:
The Victory I-class Star Destroyer, also known as the Victory I-class Destroyer and Victoria I-class Star Destroyer, was a warship designed for planetary defense, planetary assault, ground troop support, and ship-to-ship combat. It was used by the Galactic Republic during the mid-Clone Wars, the Galactic Empire and the Corporate Sector during the Galactic Civil War and the Confederation during the Second Galactic Civil War.

Victory I-class Star Destroyers were 900 meters long, just over half the size of the later Imperial-class Star Destroyer. Unlike later Star Destroyer designs, the Victory possessed the ability to enter the upper levels of a planetary atmosphere. This gave the ship a decided advantage of added precision when engaging in the ground attack operations the class was designed to carry out. In addition, the Victory could also pursue other vessels hoping to escape by diving towards a planet. A set of atmospheric maneuvering surfaces were located along the ship's flanks as well. Some Victory variants dispensed with the atmospheric maneuvering surfaces altogether. Star Destroyers of this kind fought in the Operation Shadow Hand, notably in the Battle of Balmorra.

Design:

  • Based off "Aether riveter" concept art by Cynthia Sheppard. Though in reality riveters most often use pneumatic pressure to shoot pieces of metal, this is a rotary tool used primarily as a drill. "Shine bright, bolts tight"--and keep those pesky gremlins outta your aether!
  • This is a handheld version that could be clipped to the belt of a Renegade inventor. Additionally, it's modified for greater durability, hand size, and ability to hold (and change) batteries and lights. Since it's a handheld version, there's also a mounting area in the back for an aether storage canister.
  • Spinning head for securing your rivets tight--don't let those gremlins eat into your aether supply.

Making it:

  • Print the parts with support, flat sides down. I used ABS filament at 10% infill. (Warning: remove support material carefully on the filigree surrounding the tube since filigree is delicate!)
  • Use your choice of smoothing method (auto body filler-primer, sandpaper, XTC mixture etc.) to smooth out the surface
  • Paint
  • Blue polycarbonate tube (http://www.tapplastics.com/product/plastics/plastic_rods_tubes_shapes/lamp_guards/275)
  • Screw parts together using 4-40 screws and securing nuts.

Optional section for lights and motion:
6V DC motor (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00CFSZAHS/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
6V battery holder (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GYWNM5I/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1)

  • Wrap string of lights in bubble wrap or the light diffusing material of your choice and insert into the lighting tube. Make sure the battery pack's switch is exposed so you can turn it on and off.

Enjoy!

description.text:
The Broadside-class shared a common keel design with the Gladiator-class Star Destroyer. Designed for long-range engagements, ships of this class had light armor and unimpressive acceleration and maneuverability. They were armed with missile launchers and two turbolasers.

Early models were armed with expensive diamond boron missiles that could be used to deadly effect against formations of tightly-packed ships. The range of the missiles made them very useful in long-range attacks. These weapons were replaced by more economical concussion missiles in later models, though some of the cruisers still kept their lethal armament. The payload was 1,200 missiles.
The cruiser, despite its poor maneuverability, was useful at firing long range missiles under enemy radar. This would leave the enemy confused with the sudden concentration of missiles bombarding their ships. Many Broadside-class cruisers, placed strategically where enemy radar would not detect them, could easily bring down a sizable fleet with a heavy flurry of concussion missiles, or at least bring down their shields leaving them vulnerable to attack.

title: Anet A8 I3 J-Head Bowden Adapter

description.text: This is a very simple adapter that allows you to connect a 5mm male connector quick fitting to the top of a j-head style extruder for a Bowden setup.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Anet A8

Doesn't Matter

No

0.1 Layer Height

25% Lines

Notes:

You'll get best results printing this in ABS, which is a denser/softer plastic and less prone to cracking.

On the left is an old threaded nozzle throat, on the right a 5mm male thread pneumatic quick fitting. Parts and installation instructions....
  1. Print the adapter.
  2. Screw the male end of the quick fitting into the smaller hole on your printed adapter. Make sure it's screwed far enough in that's it's flush with the face of the adapter.
  3. Screw your printed adapter onto the threaded throat WITH THE PTFE LINER REMOVED. Use the bigger hole in the adapter. It doesn't need to go in more than a few turns to be secure.
  4. Screw the threaded throat end in to the top of your j-head.

That's it! The adapter doesn't have any threads, but that didn't seem to be a problem when screwing the threaded throat or quick fitting in. Just keep it straight as you screw it in, and you're golden. If you do have difficulty with the threaded throat, I used a pair of needle nose pliars to keep it steady. As long as you keep it straight, filament will feed smoothly through the entire mess.

Screw the quick fitting in till it's flush. Use needle-nose pliars to keep the threaded throat steady. It looks like crap, but who the hell cares? It works.

I suppose you could use a shorter threaded tube, but it ain't important.
I used 123D Design to create it, and CURA as my slicer.

description.text:
A case for the iPhone 7. The two-print case is designed to be printed using PLA or ABS, both pieces slide smoothly into the phone without damaging or even touching the buttons nor the camera. The single print cases are made for flexible materials.

The one I made for my phone was printed in white PLA and Wood PLA having both pieces printed standing up and at .2mm layer height, 100% infill, but I think you could print it in any position and still get good results. Have in mind to be careful while removing the case from the phone if you use very brittle materials. I recommend printing slowly.

Some sanding may be needed for the two pieces to fit better or to have a nicer surface. You could also break the area between the side buttons and the screen if you find it difficult to press the buttons.

I've also added the SolidWorks version of the files in case you wish to modify them.

Feedback is appreciated.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.2mm or .1mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

I used a Robo 3D R1 Plus, PLA and Wood PLA.
Print slowly.
